Distributed Web Infrastructure

Diagram
User -> DNS (www.foobar.com) -> HAproxy Load Balancer -> Nginx Server 1 / Nginx Server 2 -> Application Server 1 / Application Server 2 -> MySQL Primary -> MySQL Replica

Why these elements are added
- Load balancer: distributes traffic across multiple servers to improve availability and capacity.
- Two web/application servers: provide redundancy and share the traffic load.
- Primary-replica database: keeps one writable database and one copy for redundancy and reads.

Load balancing
- Algorithm: round robin.
- How it works: each new request is sent to the next server in the list in a repeating cycle.

Cluster mode
- This is an active-active setup because both servers receive traffic at the same time.
- Active-active means both nodes are serving requests.
- Active-passive means one node is on standby until the active node fails.

Database replication
- The primary node accepts writes.
- The replica node receives data from the primary and can be used for redundancy and reads.
- The application writes to the primary and reads can be distributed depending on the design.

Issues
- SPOF still exists on the load balancer if only one is used.
- No firewall means weak security.
- No HTTPS means traffic is unencrypted.
- No monitoring means failures and performance issues may go unnoticed.
